SIMPLE: wallow
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wallow
<hw>Wal"low</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Wallowed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Wallowing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>walwen</ets>, AS. <ets>wealwian</ets>; akin to Goth.
<ets>walwjan</ets> (in comp.) to roll, L. <ets>volvere</ets>; cf. Skr.
<ets>val</ets> to turn. ⟦root⟧147. Cf. <er>Voluble Well</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To roll one's self about, as in mire; to tumble and
roll about; to move lazily or heavily in any medium; to flounder;
<as>as, swine <ex>wallow</ex> in the mire</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I may <qex>wallow</qex> in the lily beds.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To live in filth or gross vice; to disport one's
self in a beastly and unworthy manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God sees a man <qex>wallowing</qex> in his native impurity.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To wither; to fade.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. &
Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wallow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wallow
<hw>Wal"low</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To roll; esp., to roll in
anything defiling or unclean.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Wallow</xex> thyself in
ashes.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Jer. vi. 26.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wallow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wallow
<hw>Wal"low</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A kind of rolling walk.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One taught the toss, and one the new French <qex>wallow</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Act of wallowing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A place to which an animal comes to wallow; also,
the depression in the ground made by its wallowing; <as>as, a buffalo
<ex>wallow</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wallower</ent>⟦br⟧
